Exercise 1: Browser Automation and Resilient Data Extraction
EX-001-RPA
Build a Playwright-based automation solution that authenticates against a target healthcare reporting system, navigates its interface, extracts report data under various filter configurations, and writes structured output to local folders. The primary objective is not the data itself — it is to demonstrate a range of resilience and engineering techniques that make browser automation production-worthy.

The problem domain of building flexible automation solutions on top of browser interaction is more complex than it appears at first glance. Clean element IDs, stable CSS paths, and reliable DOM hierarchies rarely exist in real-world target systems. This exercise asks you to confront that reality directly and demonstrate multiple techniques for making your automation resilient in the face of it.

The Target System
The target application is a healthcare reporting system built with Angular 21 and PrimeNG. It is a static, client-side application populated with synthetic data and designed exclusively for automation exercises. It contains no real patient information.

The system exposes six report types, each with sortable and paginated data tables, configurable date range filters, dropdown filters, and export functionality:

Claim Status — claims by payer, status, date of service, billed and paid amounts
Encounters — patient encounters with diagnosis codes, procedure codes, and facility
Current AR (Accounts Receivable) — aging buckets by payer and patient
Remittance / Payments — EOB and ERA payment summaries
Denials — denied claims requiring follow-up, with denial codes and action items
Prior Authorizations — authorization status for procedures, with effective date ranges
